\":\"**Analyzing Anonymous Classes**\\n\\nI’m looking at an alternative for an anonymous creator using `new Creator[NoopActor] { ... }`. It has a declared constructor but no public access, which simplifies the class, although its name shows up as `$anon$`. I realize I might not need direct reflection, and I could create it through an instance method rather than a static one to allow closure. But I wonder if Scala 2.13 will still capture the outer context if there’s no reference to `this`. It feels tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Scala classes**\\n\\nI'm mentally testing Scala local classes and wondering if the final class AbstractPropsTest$LocalClosingCreator$1 might be public. I think the constructor could also be public? Scala classes seem to be public, even for local ones. Would getConstructors return a public constructor? I remember that local classes in Java don't have modifiers, but I wonder if Scala on the JVM marks them as public. There's definitely a lot to unpack here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_nX2VQk3pkn8LMZsTGOrFLsCn|fc_0761881ea5089f5a016a40a67404608190bd9b12daefc6f54e", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge3/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.6.0/main/extracted/org/apache/pekko/actor/Props.scala", "offset": 1, "limit": 130}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 469, "output": 1288, "cacheRead": 18432, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 20189, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782621795924, "responseId": "resp_0761881ea5089f5a016a40a66445848190a20f03e28bfa0e2d"}}
