[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring Actor Extensions**\n\nI’m considering extending AbstractActor and implementing createReceive, or maybe it's easier to just use the Actor trait. I see that Actor has a receive partial. It might be helpful to utilize AbstractActor.emptyBehavior. I need to test things and check the setup with props, specifically how local classes behave in Scala. They seem to capture the outer context, which is interesting—like how it connects to enclosing classes and methods. It’s quite a puzzle!\n\n**Analyzing Anonymous Classes**\n\nI’m looking at an alternative for an anonymous creator using `new Creator[NoopActor] { ... }`. It has a declared constructor but no public access, which simplifies the class, although its name shows up as `$anon$`. I realize I might not need direct reflection, and I could create it through an instance method rather than a static one to allow closure. But I wonder if Scala 2.13 will still capture the outer context if there’s no reference to `this`. It feels tricky!\n\n**Evaluating Scala classes**\n\nI'm mentally testing Scala local classes and wondering if the final class AbstractPropsTest$LocalClosingCreator$1 might be public. I think the constructor could also be public? Scala classes seem to be public, even for local ones. Would getConstructors return a public constructor? I remember that local classes in Java don't have modifiers, but I wonder if Scala on the JVM marks them as public. There's definitely a lot to unpack here!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0761881ea5089f5a016a40a664d9788190a181fc88b636099e\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqQKZ0rviNONBABlObh-ZLkx0tdrVZ78H5NmQ5oBpcL8mT5-RS7c2jT4EWboVQYQHfEYao7UpfYh6dwtPxoGwi8TAaXJmOdmC4VUBnEU0iQCQ0iXI_VEbXjeGyCWAUkts1sECP6MJzITdVYM_prf4SKOs-tr8kII3TA6xyicPt7EgA4OqAAhD7yOVQ6viibL4tZT_Y_ggph7z19bHyykQ9DR086lmhnjSj2NG3eNdPV729HAxYxhwyuD2HDaE5cas5bG