mpanion doesn’t exist, meaning the private constructor may not be accessible outside its class. I'll need to adjust my understanding.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring constructor access in Scala**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how access qualifiers work in Scala. If I use `private[AbstractPropsTest]`, it raises some questions. What if I had a private nested class with a public constructor? Would `getConstructors` return that? But constructors in a private class could still be public. In Scala, a class’s primary constructor shares its access level with the class itself, so if the class is private, the constructor might still be public. \\n\\nI’m considering using a companion object to create instances of a private class. It should compile fine.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Accessing private constructors**\\n\\nI'm considering how to access a private constructor through a companion object. I’m fine with using a method to avoid conflicts. For instance, I could have a method called `privateConstructorCreator()` to create an instance of `NoopActor` by calling `PrivateConstructorCreator.create()`. Now, can I nest the object and class with the same name? In Scala, it seems I can have companions in the same scope, so that should work!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class structure**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the order of `private object` and `private final class`, wondering if it makes sense to have a specific arrangement. Also, I'm contemplating whether the companion can be placed before or after these definitions. It's a tiny detail, but I want to make sure everything is structured correctly. So, let’s go ahead and edit the code to see how it flows!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_GhQEIrxq1gUkJzPrnGSY3wTT|fc_0761881ea5089f5a016a40a6c8d168819096146fd672fefeac", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.6.0/src/test/scala/org_apache_pekko/pekko_actor_2_13/AbstractPropsTest.